# Hebrew (RTL) Guidelines

## Document Setup
Always set RTL at the document root:
```tsx
<html lang="he" dir="rtl">
```

## Font Selection
```css
font-family: 'Rubik', 'Heebo', 'Assistant', system-ui, sans-serif;
```

**Rubik** is the primary font - modern, clean, excellent Hebrew support.

## CSS Best Practices for RTL

### Use Logical Properties
```css
/* ✅ Logical properties (auto-flip for RTL) */
margin-inline-start: 1rem;
padding-inline-end: 2rem;
border-inline-start: 2px solid;
text-align: start;

/* ❌ Physical properties (won't flip) */
margin-left: 1rem;
padding-right: 2rem;
border-left: 2px solid;
text-align: left;
```

### Tailwind RTL Classes
```tsx
// Use RTL-aware utilities
className="ms-4"      // margin-inline-start
className="me-4"      // margin-inline-end
className="ps-4"      // padding-inline-start
className="pe-4"      // padding-inline-end
className="start-0"   // inset-inline-start
className="end-0"     // inset-inline-end
```

## Icons & Direction
Icons that imply direction should flip:
```tsx
// Arrows, chevrons, progress indicators
className="rtl:rotate-180"
```

## Mixed Content
Handle Hebrew + English/Numbers properly:
```tsx
// Numbers stay LTR
<span dir="ltr">123</span>

// English phrases in Hebrew context
<span dir="ltr">Next.js</span>
```

## Testing RTL
- Test all layouts in RTL mode
- Verify text alignment
- Check icon directions
- Test with real Hebrew content
- Validate number display
